ur parent&#8217;s intuition tells you that Chad is very different from the =
other High Schoolers. Heck, in some ways, he&#8217;s very different from th=
e Preschoolers.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The Preschoolers are idio=
ts, relatively speaking. They can hardly form a sentence. They can&#8217;t =
do basic multiplication. But they know what they want. They wake up in the =
morning and wake their parents up to play. They go to school and play with =
the other kids, they even invent their own games and languages without anyo=
ne telling them to. They get sad when someone is mean to them, and overjoye=
d when someone gives them an ice cream cone.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rg=
b(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The=
y have agency and goals, even if they&#8217;re little goals: get ice cream,=
 get a new toy, stay up past bedtime, whatever.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
That agency and those goals scale as the kids get older.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;"><span>The High Schoolers who would be Chad&#8217;s classmates if =
he could get out of bed and go to school are wild. On the weekend, they sne=
ak out, steal their parents&#8217; cars, and go to parties, where they try =
to kiss other wild High Schoolers. During the week, they&#8217;re starting =
to figure out what they want to do with their lives &#8211; where they want=
 to go to college, what fascinates them, what kind of impact they want to h=
ave on the world. They&#8217;re nowhere near as </span><em>smart </em><span=
>as Chad, but they have a vivacity you&#8217;ve never once seen in your ver=
y smart boy.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If Chad is ever really going=
 to make something of himself, you&#8217;re going to need to figure out how=
 to get him to be more like those other kids, to have his own goals and des=
ires, even just to get out of bed of his own volition in the morning and st=
art doing things without anyone having to ask. But no matter what you try, =
you can&#8217;t, so you focus on what you can do: making Chad really fuckin=
g smart.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Maybe, you hope, at some point, if he g=
ets smart enough, he&#8217;ll see all the other kids wanting things and doi=
ng things and start to want and do things himself.&#160;</p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;">In the meantime, though, your neighbors start to see how smart Chad is g=
etting, and they start to ask him for help with all sorts of things.&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
